# The Book of Music

*\"We call it music, but we're really dealing with sound.\"*

This book teaches you to write music in Motoi Scheme by teaching you to
think about sound in time. It is a standalone book — it does not assume
you read the Scheme book first. Chapter 1 introduces the small piece of
the language you need, chapter 2 adds a little more, and so on. The
language grows only when the music needs it to.

The book has a summit. The last chapter is the first movement of
Rachmaninoff's Piano Concerto No. 2 in C minor, note for note, in
Motoi Scheme. Everything between here and there is a rung on the
ladder that gets you to a place where playing it makes sense.

Between here and the summit, the rungs are the world's musical
languages. Melody. Jazz voicing. Polyphony. Polyrhythm — clave,
three-against-two, the calypso pulse, the funk push. World percussion,
from West African bell patterns to Japanese bamboo to Indian tala.
Ornamentation, dynamics, orchestration, and the shape of a piece as a
whole. Each of these is a real genre with real conventions, and each
one gives you a new way to think about what a program that makes sound
can be.

*I think about music the way I think about a garden. There are seeds
— small ideas — and there is time. When I plant a seed and let it
grow in time, something living comes out. A note is a seed. A phrase
is a small planting. A whole piece is a garden that took a long walk
to get where it is going. You will hear me say \"seed\" and \"grow\" and
\"shape\" more than \"compose\" — that is why.*

## What this book teaches (and what it does not)

This book teaches how to **make sound with Motoi Scheme** and how to
**think in the small musical idioms** the language was built to
express. It is instrument-agnostic — you will call for a piano, a
cello, a hand drum, a bamboo flute, but you will not learn the deep
inner engineering of any single instrument here. That belongs to the
Book of Sound (the book on the shelf next to this one).

- **Here:** melody, rhythm, harmony, polyphony, polyrhythm, form,
  ornamentation, dynamics, orchestration — the musical mind.
- **Not here:** synthesis internals, envelope math, formant tables,
  the roster of every playable instrument. Those live in the Book of
  Sound.

The rule of thumb: if the idea would still be a good idea if you
translated the piece from piano to marimba, the idea belongs here. If
the idea is about what makes a marimba sound like a marimba, it
belongs in the Book of Sound.

## The public-domain rule

Every worked piece in this book is either public-domain or an original
composed for the book. Twinkle Twinkle Little Star (chapter 3) is
public-domain and safe to teach with. Rachmaninoff's Piano Concerto
No. 2, Op. 18, first published in 1901, is public-domain in the
United States and most of Europe. Where a chapter would otherwise have
used a copyrighted piece, we have written an equivalent in the same
style. The book will always tell you which it is.

## The first five chapters

1. [[#chapter-1]] **Sound and time** — what music is at ground level.
2. [[#chapter-2]] **Melody** — pitch sequences, single-voice.
3. [[#chapter-3]] **Twinkle on piano** — the payoff of the first three.
4. [[#chapter-4]] **Jazz and swing** — introducing rhythmic complexity.
5. [[#chapter-5]] **Calypso, soca, funk** — the polyrhythm door.

After chapter five the genre ladder continues, one rung at a time,
until Rachmaninoff.

## How to read

Every fenced Scheme block runs. In the browser build, click Run and
the sound plays through the page's speaker. In a terminal, paste the
block into `motoi-scheme repl` and hit Enter. The first time a page
plays audio it will ask for a click — browsers require a user gesture
before they let a page make sound. That is the only friction; after
one click the whole book plays.

Every example is a **standalone program**. You should never have to
paste the previous block first for the current block to run. If a
program needs setup, the setup is inside the block.

> **Tip**
>
> If nothing plays, the audio gesture has not been granted yet. Click
> once on the page (or type a form into the REPL) and try again. The
> engine returns `'pending-audio` on the silent first call — that is
> honest, not broken.

## What comes after chapter 5

Chapters 6 through 15 are the rest of the ladder: polyphony, world
percussion (West African bell patterns, Japanese bamboo, Indian
tala), ornamentation, dynamics, orchestration, and form. Chapter 16
is the Rach 2 summit. Each of those chapters is a rung — none of them
is the point on its own. The point is that by the time you are
holding the whole ladder, you can write anything you want.

## Cross-links

